<TITLE> Ctg BDR trial set to begin </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, Apr 21 (bdnews24.com) Trial of 110 BDR members of 10 Rifles Battalion in Chittagong, for siding with BDR mutineers in Pilkhana, Dhaka during the bloody events on Feb 25-26, 2009, is set to begin on Thursday. The BDR Special Court-4, set up at Baitul Ijjat BDR Training Centre in Satkania, will also try the accused members of the training centre and those from Naikhyangchhari's Rifles Battalion-15. The trial will begin at 10am with the outgoing Bangladesh Rifles director general Maj Gen Moinul Islam as the head of the judges' panel, staff officer of Chittagong sector headquarters Maj Sajjadul Kabir said Wednesday. But he did not mention the names of two others. bdnews24.com Bandarban correspondent, quoting the battalion commander Lt Col Robiul Hossain, reported that the detained 110 members of Rifles Battalion-10, in Bolipara under Thanchi upazila, were currently in jail. Moreover, the 40 accused members of Rifles Battalion-15 at Naikhyangchhari were detained in jail. In another case filed against the 100 members of Satkania Training Centre, one of whom died in jail, were detained at Chittagong jail. The Pilkhana mutiny saw over 70 people killed, 57 of them army officers deputed to the border force. On Nov 15 last year, the government formed six special courts, including two in Dhaka, to try about 3,500 border guards accused in 40 cases around the country. The six special courts have been trying charges of mutiny, loot and arson. In the event of a conviction, the maximum penalty for rebellion under the BDR Act is seven years in jail. The Pilkhana murders will be tried separately in civilian courts. bdnews24.co
